<article id="post-1046" class="post-1046 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-uncategorized tag-advice tag-personal-development">
	<header class="entry-header">
		<h1 class="entry-title">Giving grace</h1>

				<div class="entry-meta">
			<span class="sep">Posted on </span><a href="http://facio.com/blog/2013/04/giving-grace/" title="12:00 pm" rel="bookmark"><time class="entry-date" datetime="2013-04-23T12:00:12+00:00" pubdate>April 23, 2013</time></a><span class="by-author"> <span class="sep"> by </span> <span class="author vcard"><a class="url fn n" href="http://facio.com/blog/author/dirk/" title="View all posts by Dirk" rel="author">Dirk</a></span></span>		</div><!-- .entry-meta -->
			</header><!-- .entry-header -->

	<div class="entry-content">
		<p>My friend Bo used to encourage me to give grace, to myself and to others. It is great advice that I was reminded of when <a href="http://www.thestar.com/life/2013/04/17/dove_video_ad_shows_women_are_more_beautiful_than_they_think.html" target="_blank">watching this video</a>.</p>
<figure class="alignleft" style="width: 300px;"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-488" title="Giving grace" src="http://facio.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/Grace.png" alt="Giving grace" /></p>
<figcaption>We are terribly hard on ourselves. We needn&#8217;t be.</figcaption>
</figure>
<p>Leaving my skepticism on the shelf &#8211; the creator of the video, Dove, is part of an industry that fosters the same insecurities they are raising awareness of &#8211; the video illustrates how hard we are on ourselves. Rather than giving ourselves grace &#8211; focusing on the things we like, de-emphasizing or at least proportionally acknowledging the things we don&#8217;t &#8211; most of us in the western first world are hard on ourselves. It&#8217;s one of the byproducts of the values underlying success in the free market. We have learned to obsess and feel shame about our failings while overlooking all of the lovely things that each and every one of us have to offer.</p>
<p>There is very little to gain by flogging ourselves for being something other than who we are. While behaviours unhealthy to ourselves and others should be acknowledged and mitigated, otherwise we are best-served by just accepting who we are and leveraging our positives. It will provide us with uniformly improved happiness and well-being, while positioning us in a more confident and positive light with those we love, live and work with. At the core, it is about giving ourselves grace.</p>
<p>But we, ourselves, are only part of the equation. One of the mistakes I still frequently make is being disappointed in people who don&#8217;t do things how I would do them. Let me give you an example. On Twitter, when people converse with me, 99% of the time I&#8217;m going to respond and acknowledge them. I don&#8217;t care if I follow them or not, don&#8217;t care who or what they are. If they take the time to genuinely engage me in some way I want to show them the respect and appreciation of acknowledgement. Well, recently I sent a message to someone I don&#8217;t know, complimenting them and trying in a very small way to engage. Days passed; they did not respond. It materially changed the way I felt toward them. I was even embarrassed to not be responded to and deleted my original tweet!</p>
<p>What a shame. I have no way of knowing why that person didn&#8217;t respond to me. The odds that it was for some reason that I would actually find hurtful &#8211; they think I&#8217;m not worthy of the time &#8211; are quite low. There are dozens of other, very benign, reasons they didn&#8217;t acknowledge me. Yet, I put my own framing on the situation and chose to have negative feelings: about them, about the situation, and about myself. Isn&#8217;t it ridiculous? Why do we assume the worst? Why do we not give others the grace to be themselves?</p>
<p>As I get older, I am less apt to shenanigans such as that example. But it is hard to just naturally and easily give others grace. It is not how we are generally taught, and we are making ourselves vulnerable by leaning into that possible weakness or embarrassment. In most cases, though, that vulnerability is unlikely to turn into something actually hurtful. Instead, by foregoing our fear, we have less negative energy, more self-assuredness, and are treating ourselves and others better. It&#8217;s a no brainer, really, but often easier said than done. When in doubt, give yourself (or them) grace!</p>
			</div><!-- .entry-content -->

